unittitle.value: United Automobile Workers of America, District 65 Records

abstract.value: The labor union now known as District 65, UAW, was organized in 1933, by Arthur Osman and in 1938 became Local 65 of the United Retail and Wholesale Employees of America, CIO. In 1948, Local 65's leadership refused to sign the Taft-Hartley Act's non-communist affidavits, and Local 65, seceded from its parent union and the CIO but rejoined in 1954 as District 65 of the RWDSU (Retail, Wholesale and Department Store Union). In 1969, differences, including the union's opposition to the Vietnam War, led to District 65's disaffiliation from the RWDSU and the formation of the National Council of Distributive Workers of America. In 1979, District 65 joined the United Automobile Workers. Though at first primarily composed of Jewish workers, the union expanded to include persons of various geographical and ethnic backgrounds from the retail and manufacturing sectors, clerical personnel, salesclerks, writers, editors, technicians, and lawyers. The collection contains minutes, shop files, arbitrations, grievances, counsel files, membership information and reports, financial material, and the records of some of the unions that were affiliated with District 65 throughout its history.

p.value: Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date; United Automobile Workers, District 65; WAG 006; box number; folder number; <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.
Additional materials were donated circa 1995, by various individuals circa 2002, and found in repository in 2019.

<chronlist><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1933</date><event>Workers at H. Eckstein & Sons organize the Wholesale Dry Goods Employees Union.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Feb 1935</date><event>WDGEU affiliates with the AFL as Federal Local 19932.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jan 1936</date><event>Union drafts Arthur Osman as full-time executive secretary.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jul 1937</date><event>Union adopts resolution to affiliate with the CIO.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Aug 1937</date><event>WDGEU merges with AFL Shoe Warehouse Local and CIO Textile Warehouse Workers Union to form United Wholesale and Warehouse Employees of N.Y.'s Local 65.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1937</date><event>D65 becomes local of the United Retail and Employees of America.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Nov 1938</date><event>CIO Local 220, United Wholesale Grocery Employees merges with Local 65.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Mar 1939</date><event>Union reorganizes along a geographic rather than an industrial basis.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jun 1939</date><event>First major organization drive begins -- goal of 2500 members in one year.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Feb 1940</date><event>Union establishes Hiring Hall.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jun 1940</date><event>Union achieves first organizing drive goal. A new drive, "10,000 by 41", begins.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1940</date><event>CIO Local 353, China and Glass Workers merges with 65.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jun 1941</date><event>Union membership reaches 10,000.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">1942-1945</date><event>Union takes "No Strike" pledge.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">May 1942</date><event>Union purchases building at 13 Astor Place.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jul 1943</date><event>Union reverts to industry (local) groupings.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1945</date><event>Union inaugurates Security Plan.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Aug 1947</date><event>Union solicits $500,000 strike fund to fortify 65 against anti-labor attacks.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Jul 1948</date><event>Union officers decide not to sign Taft-Hartley non- communist affidavits.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1948</date><event>65 and seven other locals secede from the URWDSEA. They form the Distributive Trade Council with Osman as president.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Nov 1948</date><event>65 reverts to a territorial structure as defense against raiding</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Feb 1950</date><event>Local 65 mergers with seven other locals to form the Distributive Workers Union. Osman heads international; David Livingston becomes president of 65.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Apr 1950</date><event>65 leaders sign non-communist affidavits.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Oct 1950</date><event>DWU merges with the Food, Tobacco and Agricultural Workers Union and the United Office and Professional Workers of America to form the Distributive, Processing and Office Workers of America. Local 65 becomes District 65.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">May 1952</date><event>Union adopts a dual structure of organization --a combination of local and geographical alignments.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1953</date><event>Union divides into four locals or sections.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">May 1954</date><event>District 65 rejoins the RWDSU.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Sep 1963</date><event>Union shifts from local to area structure.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Apr 1969</date><event>District 65 withholds per capita in move to disaffiliate from RWDSU. Union forms new national organization, Distributive Workers of America.</event></chronitem><chronitem><date calendar="gregorian" era="ce">Aug 1979</date><event>65 affiliates with the UAW.</event></chronitem></chronlist>
